It's officially in the logbook. I flew 2.3 hours ^_^
#TeaganAir
If I had to describe to you what it's like to fly a small aircraft, I would say it's like a mixture of a motorcycle/quad and a boat, 4,000 feet in the air.
On the ground, you're immediately very fast. Everything is somewhat unstable on the ground, hence motorcycle/quad.
And if you didn't know yet: You steer a plane on the ground with your feet, not with the control stick. Rudder pedals and brakes. It's not a car.
In the air it's wobbly and you're sort of swimming. It feels like being in a boat on the water. You can steer it, but sometimes a wave comes and throws you off course a little, so you have to get used to the sea conditions, only in the air.
Another random detail:
Flying is physically exhausting. Today my back and my legs *hurt* as if I had been at the gym.
This isn't like a Sunday car trip. It's more like a sport than a walk, in my newly gained opinion.
A beautiful Saturday, my loves. Welcome to 4,000 feet.
Tomorrow I will go again. Then we will practice stalls and slow flying.
Today the weather was unsettled, but it was a lot of fun. We practiced slow flying and stalls. Once we had a ground speed of only 16 mph with an airspeed of 65.
It was a beautiful clear day, a bit hazy higher up, but still nice.
